"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712437","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-23","<p>We have no plans to do this.</p><p> </p><p>TB in dogs, caused by <em>Mycobacterium bovis</em> (the bovine TB bacterium), is extremely rare and dogs pose a very low risk of transmitting the disease.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-23T11:00:15.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712437/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712437/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-20","Bovine Tuberculosis: Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to cancel all hunting activities until foxhound packs across the UK are certified to be free of TB.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","68538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712438","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-23","<p>An epidemiological investigation into this incident is underway.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-23T10:44:12.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712438/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712438/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-20","Bovine Tuberculosis: Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to investigate the source of the bovine TB outbreak within Kimblewick Hunt's foxhound packs.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","68536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712439","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-23","<p>Bovine TB is a notifiable disease in all farmed and pet mammal species, including dogs. The disease has only very rarely been diagnosed in dogs, in this country and elsewhere, and investigations into bovine TB breakdowns in cattle herds have never identified the source of a breakdown as an infected dog.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-23T17:35:22.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712439/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712439/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-20","Dogs: Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2017 to Question 67006 on bovine tuberculosis: dogs, whether her Department has carried out any research on diseases in packs of hunting dogs.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","68511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712440","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-23","<p>This control has been in place for some time for all pet and farmed mammals. Under the Tuberculosis (England) Order 2014 the detection of suspect TB lesions in carcases and the identification of <em>Mycobacterium bovis</em> from tissue or other samples (including dogs) is notifiable.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-23T10:47:14.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712440/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712440/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-20","Bovine Tuberculosis: Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy for TB in hunt packs operating in close proximity to cattle to be a notifiable disease.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","68537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712441","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-27","<p>The European Commission has now recognised the four substances as endocrine-disrupting chemicals for human health. This scientific assessment was supported by the UK and is in line with our policy approach towards chemicals management.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","68400","2017-03-27T09:40:49.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712441/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712441/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-20","Chemicals: Hazardous Substances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the implications for her Department's policies of the EU REACH process identification of four synthetic chemicals, DEHIP, DIBP, DBP and BBP, as endocrine-disrupting chemicals for human health; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","68459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712442","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>As at 21 March 2017, 12 of the UK's 157 serving HM Ambassadors and High Commissioners were recruited to these roles from another UK Government Department or from outside the UK Civil Service. This represents 8 per cent of the total.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-28T14:58:18.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712442/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712442/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-20","Diplomatic Service: Career Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many and what proportion of serving HM Ambassadors and High Commissioners are not career diplomats.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","68433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712443","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>​We are in close contact with the Japanese government to find a mutually convenient date in 2017 to host the third substantive UK-Japan 2+2 Foreign and Defence Ministerial talks.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-28T14:25:28.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712443/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712443/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-20","Japan: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when his Department and the Ministry of Defence plan to hold the next two plus two meeting with the foreign and defence ministers of Japan.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","68491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712444","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-28","<p>The UK has a strong history of protecting human rights and promoting our values globally. We will consider all options in the design of future bilateral trade and investment agreements.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-03-28T16:39:21.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712444/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712444/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-20","Trade Agreements: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will take steps to ensure that human rights have equal or higher protection in UK free trade agreements as in EU free trade agreements after the UK exits the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","68503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712445","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-27","<p>There have been no formal discussions between the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) and the private sector on the construction or commissioning of a new royal yacht. A new royal yacht is not on the Government's agenda. If private money is raised, we wish donors well.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-27T15:52:41.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712445/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712445/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712445/answer/previousversion/42053","Biography information for Alok Sharma","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-20","Royal Yacht","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to his contribution on 13 March 2017, to the debate on Budget Resolutions (HC Deb, col 84), whether he has had discussions with the private sector on the construction or commissioning of a new royal yacht.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","68552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712446","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-27","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) has not had any formal discussions with the Secretary of State for Department for International Trade, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for North Somerset (Dr Fox) on the effect of a privately-funded royal yacht for securing trade deals.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-27T15:52:10.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712446/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712446/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712446/answer/previousversion/42049","Biography information for Alok Sharma","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-20","Royal Yacht","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to his contribution on 13 March 2017, to the debate on Budget Resolutions (HC Deb, col 84) and pursuant to the Answer of 18 October 2016 to Question 47643, whether he has held discussions with the Department for International Trade on the effect of a privately-funded royal yacht on securing trade deals.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","68551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712447","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson), raised the UK’s concerns about demolitions, including the village of Khan Al Ahmar, with Prime Minister Netanyahu during his visit to Israel on 8 March. The Israeli High Court has approved a temporary injunction extending the deadline for the demolition order against the structures in Khan Al Ahmar to March 30.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-23T15:38:12.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712447/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712447/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-20","Occupied Territories: Demolition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his counterpart in Israel to reverse demolition orders relating to the village of Khan Al Ahmar in the Occupied Palestinian Territories.","false","Biography information for John Glen","Salisbury","John Glen","68542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712448","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>​ I refer the Hon. Member to my response to Written Question 65641 of of 7 March.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-28T16:44:36.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712448/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712448/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-20","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2017 to Question 65641, on Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Brexit, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations are within his Department's remit, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","68531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712449","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>​It is Mr Tsege's right and wish to have access to legal advice and that is why we have pursued this for him. I am pleased that, on 15 March, Mr Tsege had an introductory meeting with a lawyer, allowing him to discuss his options under Ethiopian law.</p><p>The Ethiopian and Yemeni authorities have both stated that they have a bilateral treaty that permits Mr Tsege's extradition to Ethiopia. Although we have requested sight of it, we have not seen this agreement and are not in a position to form a view as to the legality of the process in this case.</p><p>Our consular priorities continue to be Mr Tsege's wellbeing, his access to legal representation, and to ensure that the death sentence is not carried out.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-23T14:14:30.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712449/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712449/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-20","Andargachew Tsege","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the legality of Andy Tsege's (a) trial, (b) arrest and rendition and (c) detention.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","68600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712450","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>The nuclear and ballistic missile programmes of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) clearly violate multiple UN Security Council Resolutions. Following a ballistic missile launch on 11 February the DPRK Ambassador was summoned to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office where it was made clear that their actions are a threat to international security and that such dangerous and destabilising activity must stop. The Ambassador was asked to convey this message to Pyongyang in the strongest possible terms.</p><p>As the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) stated after the DPRK's ballistic missile launch on 5 March, we urge DPRK to stop their provocative actions, which threaten international peace and security.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-28T14:27:43.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712450/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712450/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-20","North Korea: Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to North Korea on recent nuclear missile tests in that country.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","68573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712451","Department of Health","false","2017-03-27","<p>The information is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to define those employed at National Health Service mental health units because the delivery of services by NHS staff is only captured at trust level, not hospital or site level.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","68572","2017-03-27T10:03:02.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712451/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712451/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Health Professions: York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many full-time equivalent NHS (a) consultants, (b) junior hospital doctors, (c) nurses and midwives, (d) other clinical staff and (e) staff in total were employed at York hospitals, excluding mental health units in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","68576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712452","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>NHS England publishes monthly data on referral to treatment waiting times to report performance against the legal right that patients have to start consultant-led treatment within a maximum of 18 weeks from referral for non-urgent conditions.</p><p> </p><p>Waiting times for patients whose treatment started during the month and involved admission to hospital are described in the data as admitted pathways. Not all admissions to hospitals are for surgery. Waiting times for patients whose treatment started during the month and did not involve admission to hospital, for example outpatients, are described in the data as non-admitted pathways.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested for York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement advise that York NHS Foundation Trust is working to improve referral to treatment performance, with several areas of work underway such as maximising theatre and outpatient capacity and working with commissioners on managing future demand for pressurised specialties such as dermatology.</p><p> </p><p>Number and percentage of admitted pathways and non-admitted pathways longer than 18 weeks and average median waiting times at York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust in each year since 2009-10</p><p> </p><table><thead><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>Year</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Admitted pathways</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Non-admitted pathways</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of pathways more than 18 weeks</p></td><td><p>Percentage of pathways more than 18 weeks</p></td><td><p>Median waiting time (weeks) in March</p></td><td><p>Number of pathways more than 18 weeks</p></td><td><p>Percentage of pathways more than 18 weeks</p></td><td><p>Median waiting time (weeks) in March</p></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>1,439</p></td><td><p>8.8%</p></td><td><p>8.1</p></td><td><p>1,473</p></td><td><p>2.6%</p></td><td><p>3.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>1,136</p></td><td><p>6.8%</p></td><td><p>7.8</p></td><td><p>1,263</p></td><td><p>2.1%</p></td><td><p>3.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>1,584</p></td><td><p>9.9%</p></td><td><p>11.3</p></td><td><p>1,141</p></td><td><p>1.8%</p></td><td><p>3.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>1,998</p></td><td><p>8.7%</p></td><td><p>10.8</p></td><td><p>3,115</p></td><td><p>3.4%</p></td><td><p>3.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2,790</p></td><td><p>11.0%</p></td><td><p>13.2</p></td><td><p>4,642</p></td><td><p>4.5%</p></td><td><p>4.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>4,140</p></td><td><p>16.3%</p></td><td><p>12.8</p></td><td><p>4,010</p></td><td><p>4.1%</p></td><td><p>4.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>6,307</p></td><td><p>24.0%</p></td><td><p>11.6</p></td><td><p>4,606</p></td><td><p>4.8%</p></td><td><p>5.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source</em>: Consultant-led referral to treatment waiting times, NHS England</p><p><em>Notes</em>:</p><ol><li>York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust acquired Scarborough Hospital in 2012.</li></ol>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-28T16:12:44.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712452/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712452/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","York Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of patients referred to York Hospital for (a) elective surgery and (b) outpatient appointments waited longer than 18 weeks from referral to treatment in each year since 2009-10; and what the average waiting time was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","68513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712453","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>NHS England publishes monthly data on referral to treatment waiting times to report performance against the legal right that patients have to start consultant-led treatment within a maximum of 18 weeks from referral for non-urgent conditions. Waiting times for patients whose treatment started during the month and involved admission to hospital are described in the data as admitted pathways. Not all admissions to hospitals are for surgery.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number and percentage of admitted pathways longer than 26 weeks at York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust in each year since 2009-10.</p><p> </p><p>Number and percentage of admitted pathways<sup>1</sup> longer than 26 weeks at York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, 2009-10 to 2015-16</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>Number longer than 26 weeks</p></td><td><p>Percentage longer than 26 weeks</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>622</p></td><td><p>3.8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>410</p></td><td><p>2.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>769</p></td><td><p>4.8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>1,034</p></td><td><p>4.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>1,635</p></td><td><p>6.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>1,322</p></td><td><p>5.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>1,368</p></td><td><p>5.2%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: </em>Consultant-led referral to treatment waiting times, NHS England</p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><ol><li>Before October 2015, adjustments were allowable to admitted pathways for clock pauses, where a patient declined reasonable offers of admission and chose to wait longer. From October 2015, there is no provision for clock pauses under any circumstances and admitted pathways are unadjusted.</li><li>York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust acquired Scarborough Hospital in 2012.</li></ol>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-28T14:34:25.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712453/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712453/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","York Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of patients referred for elective surgery to York Hospital waited longer than six months from referral to treatment in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","68514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712454","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>We have record numbers of nurses working in the National Health Service. Since May 2010 we have seen an increase of almost 6,500 nurses in the NHS (a 2.3% increase), and there are currently over 52,000 students training to become nurses.</p><p> </p><p>We have increased the number of training places for both new and nurses returning to practice.</p><p> </p><p>Developing new routes into nursing is a priority for the Department. We have developed the new Nursing Associate role and Nursing Degree Apprenticeship which will open up routes into the registered nursing profession for thousands of people from all backgrounds and allow employers to grow their own workforce. The Nursing Associate has been designed to bridge the gap between senior healthcare support workers and registered nurses delivering hands on care and freeing up registered nurses to focus on clinical duties and using their specialist training to lead patient care. Nursing Associates will complement, not replace, Registered Nurses.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","68554","2017-03-28T16:56:28.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712454/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712454/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will introduce a second, junior tier of qualified nursing staff in order to increase the general supply of nursing staff in public hospitals.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","68559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712455","Department of Health","false","2017-03-27","<p>The General Medical Council (GMC) is consulting on proposals to introduce a United Kingdom Medical Licensing Assessment. This consultation closes in April. The Department will consider whether changes to the GMC’s rules are required in light of the outcome of the consultation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-27T10:04:07.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712455/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712455/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Doctors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of reforming the General Medical Council's licensing rules to increase the general supply of doctors in public hospitals.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","68560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712456","Department of Health","false","2017-03-27","<p>The information is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to define those employed at National Health Service mental health units because the delivery of services by NHS staff is only captured at trust level, not hospital or site level.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","68576","2017-03-27T10:03:02.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712456/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712456/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Mental Health Services: York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many full-time equivalent NHS (a) consultants, (b) junior doctors, (c) nurses, (d) other clinical staff and (e) staff in total were employed at NHS mental health units in the 2012 City of York council area in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","68572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712457","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>We have record numbers of nurses working in the National Health Service. Since May 2010 we have seen an increase of almost 6,500 nurses in the NHS (a 2.3% increase), and there are currently over 52,000 students training to become nurses.</p><p> </p><p>We have increased the number of training places for both new and nurses returning to practice.</p><p> </p><p>Developing new routes into nursing is a priority for the Department. We have developed the new Nursing Associate role and Nursing Degree Apprenticeship which will open up routes into the registered nursing profession for thousands of people from all backgrounds and allow employers to grow their own workforce. The Nursing Associate has been designed to bridge the gap between senior healthcare support workers and registered nurses delivering hands on care and freeing up registered nurses to focus on clinical duties and using their specialist training to lead patient care. Nursing Associates will complement, not replace, Registered Nurses.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","68559","2017-03-28T16:56:28.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712457/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712457/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to increase the supply of nurses in public hospitals.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","68554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712459","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Information Commissioner published a statement regarding this matter on the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) website on 21 March. There is no evidence that records have been lost, mislaid or misused.</p><p> </p><p>National Health Service organisations have been working closely with the ICO and the British Medical Association to support TPP to take appropriate mitigations to respond to the concerns raised. A number of measures are already being implemented and a full plan is expected to be in place by summer 2017.</p><p> </p><p>This software is in use in around one third of general practitioner (GP) practices in England. However, not all GP practices or their patients will be affected.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","68595","2017-03-28T16:51:13.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712459/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712459/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","General Practitioners: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with the Information Commissioner on the breach of the IT system SystmOne.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","68594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712460","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Information Commissioner published a statement regarding this matter on the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) website on 21 March. There is no evidence that records have been lost, mislaid or misused.</p><p> </p><p>National Health Service organisations have been working closely with the ICO and the British Medical Association to support TPP to take appropriate mitigations to respond to the concerns raised. A number of measures are already being implemented and a full plan is expected to be in place by summer 2017.</p><p> </p><p>This software is in use in around one third of general practitioner (GP) practices in England. However, not all GP practices or their patients will be affected.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","68594","2017-03-28T16:51:13.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712460/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712460/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","General Practitioners: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of medical records at risk of being unlawfully accessed through the SystmOne IT system managed by the company TPP.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","68595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712461","Department of Health","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Department has received no formal requests for funding from the group Action on Smoking and Health (ASH) for the next financial year.</p><p> </p><p>Grants made under Section 64 of the Health Services and Public Health Act 1968 can be made in a number of ways. For the activities delivered by the current grant, awarded to ASH, it was assessed that the non-competed tender route was most appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>Any future applications for funding under the Section 64 grant system will be reviewed by the Department in accordance with the Cabinet Office Minimum Standards which came into force in December 2016.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-23T09:54:20.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712461/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712461/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Action on Smoking and Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has received a request for funding from the group Action on Smoking and Health in respect of the next financial year; and if he will ensure that all grants awarded for such work are assessed on a competitive basis.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","68614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712462","Department of Health","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency only regulates dermal fillers that are placed on the United Kingdom market as medical devices, as defined in the Medical Devices Regulations 2002. The majority of these products are intended to be used in reconstructive surgery, and as a result they are considered to be medical devices.</p><p> </p><p>Where an unregulated medical product, including dermal fillers, is administered by a regulated medical professional, that regulated professional is subject to the standards of their registration.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-23T16:18:22.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712462/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712462/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Plastic Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to improve the regulation of dermal fillers used in non-surgical cosmetic interventions and not classified as medical devices.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","68608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712463","Department of Health","false","2017-03-27","<p>The GP Patient Survey is conducted by an independent contractor on behalf of NHS England. The current contract (2016-19) is being delivered by Ipsos MORI, as was the previous contract (2013-16). It is not appropriate to provide the precise costs paid to the survey provider, as this is commercially sensitive information. Over the contract period 2013-16, the budget of the GP Patient Survey was approximately £4 million per year. For the current contract, which began in July 2016, the budget is approximately £3.5 million per year.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-27T09:59:57.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712463/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712463/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","General Practitioners: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the public purse was of carrying out the GP Patient Survey in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","68506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712464","Department of Health","false","2017-03-27","<p>The information requested is not held by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>The General Medical Council (GMC) is the independent regulator of doctors in the United Kingdom. The GMC has confirmed that although it holds data on the number of doctors who have applied for a certificate of current professional status to work aboard, it does not hold data on the number of doctors registered to practise in the UK who actually go abroad to work in medicine.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-27T10:05:35.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712464/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712464/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","General Practitioners: Overseas Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of GPs have left the UK to work abroad within (a) one, (b) two and (c) three years of completing their training in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","68485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712465","Department of Health","false","2017-03-23","<p>In 2015/16, spend on General Practitioner Learning Disabilities Directed Enhanced Services (DES) was £12.376 million. Under the DES, patients aged 14 and over with learning disabilities are offered an annual health check, which includes producing a health action plan.</p><p> </p><p>The National Audit Office has recently estimated that the annual cost of supporting a person with challenging behaviour and learning disabilities, autism or both within an assessment and treatment unit is £180,000.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","68446","2017-03-23T17:13:36.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712465/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712465/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much funding was allocated by NHS England to the learning disability GP annual health check scheme in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","68449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712466","Department of Health","false","2017-03-23","<p>In 2015/16, spend on General Practitioner Learning Disabilities Directed Enhanced Services (DES) was £12.376 million. Under the DES, patients aged 14 and over with learning disabilities are offered an annual health check, which includes producing a health action plan.</p><p> </p><p>The National Audit Office has recently estimated that the annual cost of supporting a person with challenging behaviour and learning disabilities, autism or both within an assessment and treatment unit is £180,000.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","68449","2017-03-23T17:13:36.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712466/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712466/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the average annual cost to the public purse of supporting a person with challenging behaviour and learning disabilities, autism or both within an assessment and treatment unit.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","68446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712467","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>The following table shows a count of finished consultant episodes (FCEs)<sup>1</sup> at York Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust from 2005-06 to 2015-16.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>FCEs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-06</p></td><td><p>81,586</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>80,936</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>78,310</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>87,023</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>91,528</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>97,719</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>103,847</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>164,691</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>174,006</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>184,428</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>195,482</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source</em>: Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><ol><li>FCE is a continuous period of admitted patient care under one consultant within one healthcare provider. FCEs are counted against the year in which they end. Figures do not represent the number of different patients, as a person may have more than one episode of care within the same stay in hospital or in different stays in the same year.</li><li>York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust acquired Scarborough Hospital in 2012.</li></ol>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-28T14:42:08.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712467/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712467/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many finished consultant episodes there were at York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust in each year since 2005-06.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","68455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712468","Department of Health","false","2017-03-23","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are primarily responsible for commissioning diabetes services to meet the requirements of their populations. In doing so, CCGs need to ensure that the services they provide are fit for purpose, reflect the needs of the local population, and are based on the available evidence, taking into account national guidelines. This should include consideration of access to continuous glucose monitoring for people with type 1 diabetes who might benefit from it.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-23T09:48:15.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712468/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712468/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Diabetes: Medical Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it his policy to make continuous glucose monitors available on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","68467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712469","Department of Health","false","2017-03-23","<p>Hubs are not about surgery closures — that has never been this Government's policy intention and we are supporting general practice with a 14% real terms increase in funding. Many general practices are already working together to support larger populations and in the future there will be even more opportunities for collaboration so that practices can work at scale when necessary, while maintaining their location within communities and relationships with patients.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-23T17:17:25.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712469/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712469/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","GP Surgeries: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Health of 15 March 2017, Official Report, column 144WH, if the proposed creation of super-hubs in rural areas means the closure of local practice buildings to be replaced with new larger buildings.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","68468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712470","Department of Health","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Department can confirm following a detailed search of its Business Management Services database, that “The Evening Standard” is not a registered supplier and consequently hold no records of any spend on advertising costs since 2010 with this newspaper.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-23T15:41:20.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712470/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712470/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Department of Health: Evening Standard","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department spent on advertising with the Evening Standard newspaper in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","68444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712471","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>In accordance with the contract all accommodation providers are required to develop close and co-operative relationships with local authorities and maintain effective on-going consultation and liaison arrangements with them.</p><p>In practice providers work closely with the Home Office and regional Strategic Migration Partnerships to seek the views of local authorities on proposed addresses for asylum accommodation within dispersal areas on a range of issues including the capacity of local health, education and other support services; the concentration of service users and risk of social tensions. How the consultation is undertaken will be agreed with each local authority with the support of the Strategic Migration Partnerships.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-23T17:40:11.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712471/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712471/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, by what process (a) Serco, (b) G4S and (c) Clearel procure accommodation under the provisions of the Compass system.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","68477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712472","Home Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>In accordance with the contract accommodation providers notify the Home Office of any material sub-contractors they employ. A breakdown of the number of material sub-contractors by contract region is shown in the attached table:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of Material Sub-Contractors</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London and the South</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Midlands and East of England</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East and Yorkshire and Humberside</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>33</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland and Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-28T14:50:19.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712472/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712472/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many sub-contractors supply accommodation under the provision of the Compass system in each region.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","68478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712473","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>Responsibility for landlord insurance is a matter for the Service Providers to address via their individual arrangements with their Sub-Contractors and/or Landlords.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-23T17:40:55.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712473/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712473/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is the responsibility of (a) the contractor or (b) the landlord to cover the cost of landlord insurance under the Compass system.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","68479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712474","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>Attacks on people involving acids or other corrosives are a serious matter that can result in huge distress and life changing injuries. We are working with retailers to explore what action can be taken to control sales of products with a high acidic content, and we are also working with the National Police Chiefs’ Council lead to better understand the extent and scale of crimes involving acid to inform measures to prevent such attacks.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-03-23T17:20:14.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712474/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712474/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Crimes of Violence: Acids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to reduce the number of acid attacks.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","68460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712475","Home Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>Our records indicate that the number of individuals who received a positive conclusive grounds decision from the National Referral Mechanism who were granted discretionary leave to remain in the UK were as shown in table 1 below.</p><p> </p><p>The question has been interpreted as referring to people holding only discretionary leave status following an earlier positive conclusion grounds decision. The grant of limited leave may not have been in the same year as the positive conclusive grounds outcome.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year Positive CG Outcome Made</p></td><td><p>Granted DL</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>129</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>123</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>132</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Grand Total</p></td><td><p>384</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><ol><li>These statistics have been taken from a live operational database. As such, numbers may change as information on that system is updated.</li><li>Data showing latest case grant. Please note that the DL category includes all types of &quot;Limited Leave&quot;.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="3"><li>Data only shows those cases where the grant occurs after the positive conclusive grounds outcome.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="4"><li>A person might have been granted another form of leave such as asylum instead of a grant of DL, the asylum grant could have occurred at any point during their immigration history.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="5"><li>The data is part of a wider data set which looks at different type of grants individuals might have received using the following hierarchy - Asylum (at any point during their immigration history), HP, DL &amp; ILR (after the positive conclusive grounds stage).</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="6"><li>The National Referral Mechanism (NRM) is the process by which people who may have been victims of modern slavery are identified, referred, assessed and supported in the United Kingdom. (“Modern slavery” is a term that covers slavery, servitude and forced or compulsory labour and human trafficking.) The initial referral goes through a two stage process: a reasonable grounds stage and then, for those with a positive reasonable grounds outcome (where it is considered that the person is a potential victim of trafficking/slavery), a conclusive grounds stage (where the person is considered to be a confirmed victim of trafficking/slavery) .</li></ol><p> </p><p>We cannot determine if the grant is linked to the fact that the person was also a victim of trafficking.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-30T15:51:32.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712475/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712475/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people who passed through the National Referral Mechanism as victims of modern slavery or of human trafficking with positive conclusive grounds status were granted discretionary leave to remain in the UK in (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 1 April to 31 December 2016.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","68451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712476","Home Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>The requirement to maintain the security of an immigration removal centre (IRC) is set out in the Detention Centre Rules 2001. The published Detention Services Operating Standards set out the requirement for each IRC to have a local security strategy, which includes searching procedures to detect and deter threats to the security or control of the centre.</p><p> </p><p>The Operating Standards also require a full-length physical perimeter search to be conducted daily.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-28T14:52:06.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712476/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712476/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Detention Centres: Guard Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her policy is on use of dogs to patrol (a) immigration detention centres and (b) Dungavel immigration removal centre.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","68452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712478","Home Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Free Movement Directive requires those who wish to rely on periods of residence as a student or self-sufficient person in order to acquire permanent residence to have held comprehensive sickness insurance for the relevant qualifying periods.</p><p> </p><p>While failure to meet this EU law requirement will lead to a refusal of documentation certifying that the applicant has a right to reside, our longstanding practice is that European Economic Area (EEA) national students or self-sufficient persons will not be removed from the UK solely because they do not have comprehensive sickness insurance. This is because the failure is relatively straightforward to rectify and establish a right to reside in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Where applications for documentation are refused or rejected, the reasons are explained to applicants and they can, if they wish, apply again with the necessary supporting evidence, although we do not compel them to do so.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-28T14:53:10.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712478/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712478/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Immigration: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's policy is on whether EEA citizens will be removed from or refused re-entry to the UK on the basis that they do not have comprehensive sickness insurance; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","68486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712479","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>Yes. Those who are found to be at risk of female genital mutilation may be granted refugee status.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-23T17:39:23.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712479/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712479/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Female Genital Mutilation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is her Department's policy to recognise the threat of female genital mutilation as grounds for an asylum claim in the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","68534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712480","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Home Office does not collect data on the number of acid attacks. Acid or other corrosive attacks would be recorded though under different offence types, usually assault occasioning actual bodily harm or grievous bodily harm depending on the severity of the injuries inflicted. We are currently working with the National Police Chiefs’ Council lead to gather data through police forces to better understand the extent and scale of crimes involving acid and other corrosive substances.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-03-23T17:22:22.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712480/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712480/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Crimes of Violence: Acids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many acid attacks there were in (a) the UK, (b) Greater London and (c) the London Borough of Newham in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","68535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712481","Home Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Home Office has not spent any money on public information advertising with the Evening Standard newspaper since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>Costs relating to recruitment advertising is not held centrally, and collation of this information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-03-28T14:51:11.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712481/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712481/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Home Office: Evening Standard","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much her Department spent on advertising with the Evening Standard newspaper in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","68597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712482","Department of Health","false","2017-03-28","<p>National Health Service staff work very hard in a high pressure environment. Any abuse of staff is unacceptable and should not be tolerated. Employers in the NHS are responsible for assessing risks to staff and addressing those risks.</p><p> </p><p>Any abuse against members of NHS staff should be reported and trusts should have no hesitation in involving the police. Detailed guidance is available to NHS employers to assist them in assessing and managing the risks accordingly. Guidance includes advice on joint working between the NHS, the police and the Crown Prosecution Service on responses to incidents of abuse or violence when these occur and on taking forward appropriate cases for prosecution.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-28T09:19:04.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712482/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712482/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-20","Ambulance Services: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to reduce the number of attacks on ambulance workers in (a) England, (b) the North West and (c) Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","68566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712483","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-27","<p>Information held centrally by the Ministry of Justice does not specifically identify people convicted of attacks on ambulance workers. The information requested could therefore only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","68568","2017-03-27T10:51:01.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712483/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712483/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Crimes of Violence: Ambulance Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length of sentence was for people convicted of attacks on ambulance workers in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","68567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712484","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-27","<p>Information held centrally by the Ministry of Justice does not specifically identify people convicted of attacks on ambulance workers. The information requested could therefore only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","68567","2017-03-27T10:51:02.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712484/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712484/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Crimes of Violence: Ambulance Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were (a) prosecuted and (b) convicted of attacking ambulance workers in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","68568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712485","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-23","<p>The UK provides emergency response to communities facing demolition and displacement in Area C and East Jerusalem through core funding to the European Civil Protection and Humanitarian Aid Operations (ECHO).</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-23T17:50:42.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712485/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712485/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-20","Israel: Demolition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if her Department will take steps to provide humanitarian assistance to Palestinians displaced by the expected demolition of Khan Al Ahmar in the Occupied Palestinian Territories.","false","Biography information for John Glen","Salisbury","John Glen","68541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712486","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-27","<p>DFID works with the European Investment Bank (EIB), the EU’s financial institution, on its external lending.</p><p>While we do not have a record of staff time spent on engagement with the Bank, my department does currently support two Seconded Experts within the EIB.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-27T17:00:26.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712486/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712486/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-20","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 6 March 2017 to Question 65645, on Department for International Development: Brexit, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations are within her Department's remit, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","68520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712487","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-27","<p>The UK currently invests in supply chains through programmes like the Africa Enterprise Challenge Fund and the Global Agriculture and Food Security Programme. Support for in-country processing of basic commodities is a way to add value and support livelihoods in developing countries.</p><p>In the Economic Development Strategy launched in January 2017, DfID committed to take an increasingly dynamic approach to agriculture, including boosting agri-business and financing agricultural infrastructure, to provide strong foundations for inclusive growth. The specific support we provide to different countries and sectors will be tailored to local needs and priorities.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-27T16:55:43.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712487/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712487/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-20","Developing Countries: Manufactured Goods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department plans to use some of the UK's aid budget to support the creation of processing plants to allow start-to-finish manufacture of chocolate and coffee in countries that provide the base products for fair-trade food items.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","68475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712488","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-27","<p>We are committed to improving safety and decreasing violence across the prison estate. We do not underestimate the challenges faced by everyone working in prisons and will continue to support our staff<br> to help them maintain safe and secure prisons.</p><p>We are taking immediate action which includes tackling the use of drugs, mobile phones and drones, <br> while strengthening the frontline by recruiting an additional 2,500 staff. We are also providing over 3,400 body-worn cameras across the estate, alongside training to improve staff interactions with prisoners.</p><p>The increase in staff will provide the capacity for prison officers to play a dedicated officer role and build constructive relationships with prisoners, reduce levels of frustration and, ultimately, reduce levels of violence.</p><p>Violence in prison is a crime. Prisoners who assault our hard working staff should feel the full force of <br> the law. We are working closely with the Police and Crown Prosecution Service to ensure that offenders face swift justice and that courts have full evidence of the harm caused, in order to impose the strongest possible punishment.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-27T10:22:26.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712488/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712488/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she is taking to reduce violence against prison staff.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712489","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Prisons and Courts Bill is clear that prisons are there to deliver the sentences of the court – depriving people of their liberty to punish them for their crimes. This reflects and underlines the existing principles set out in the Criminal Justice Act 2003, which states that one of the purposes of sentencing is the punishment of offenders.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-23T17:28:47.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712489/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712489/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prisons and Courts Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what consideration was given to including punishment as a purpose of prisons in clause 1(2) of the Prisons and Courts Bill.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","68469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712490","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>On 27 February the Lord Chancellor reduced the personal injury discount rate set under section 1 of the Damages Act 1996 to minus 0.75%. The new rate came into effect on 20 March.</p><p> </p><p>The government acknowledges that the change in the rate will have significant implications across the public and private sectors and has committed to review the legal framework for the setting of the rate to ensure it remains fit for purpose in the future. A consultation paper will be published before Easter.</p><p> </p><p>Following the consultation, the government will consider whether there is a better or fairer framework for claimants and defendants, and bring forward any necessary legislation at an early stage.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","68439","2017-03-23T16:34:55.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712490/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712490/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of changes to the discount rate for motor insurance on the take-up of such insurance.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","68438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712491","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>On 27 February the Lord Chancellor reduced the personal injury discount rate set under section 1 of the Damages Act 1996 to minus 0.75%. The new rate came into effect on 20 March.</p><p> </p><p>The government acknowledges that the change in the rate will have significant implications across the public and private sectors and has committed to review the legal framework for the setting of the rate to ensure it remains fit for purpose in the future. A consultation paper will be published before Easter.</p><p> </p><p>Following the consultation, the government will consider whether there is a better or fairer framework for claimants and defendants, and bring forward any necessary legislation at an early stage.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","68438","2017-03-23T16:34:56.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712491/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712491/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of changes to the discount rate for motor insurance on the average cost of such insurance.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","68439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712492","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>Question 62919 tabled on 2 February 2017 by the hon. Member for Coventry South was answered on 23 March 2017.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-23T17:34:11.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712492/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712492/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Ministry of Justice: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she plans to answer Question 62919, tabled on 2 February 2017 by the hon. Member for Coventry South on prisoners.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712493","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-29","<p>The below EU agencies are within this department’s remit;</p><p>Fundamental Rights Agency</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This department engages with a range of stakeholders. We do not disaggregate the time and resource spent on this engagement.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-29T11:47:31.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712493/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712493/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 6 March 2017 to Question 65647, on Ministry of Justice: Brexit, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations are within her Department's remit, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","68524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712494","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-28","<p>In 2012 NOMS introduced significant reforms to their pay and grading structures through the introduction of ‘Fair and Sustainable’. The reforms included the introduction of a new job evaluation scheme, standardised job descriptions and a new pay structure and aimed to mitigate equal pay risk.</p><p> </p><p>All jobs are evaluated using the Job Evaluation Scheme (JES), and this determines the pay band the role it falls within.</p><p> </p><p>The pay for operational prison staff, including officers, is considered on an annual basis by the independent Prison Service Pay Review Body (PSPRB), based on evidence relating to private sector pay structures, public sector pay policy, recruitment and retention of staff, budget restrictions set by HM Treasury and the UK economy growth and inflation forecasts. We have however taken a number of steps to improve remuneration for prison officers over the past year, including:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Increasing the rates of Payment Plus and Tornado allowances for staff working extra hours or taking on additional duties.</li><li>Announced plans to introduce temporary market supplements to our 31 hardest to recruit sites for the remainder of this Parliament, which will boost prison offer pay by up to £5,000.</li><li>Creating 2,000 new senior positions available for promotion which provide further opportunities for officers to boost their take home pay as part of our continued plans to professionalise the workforce.</li></ul><p> </p><p>A number of prison officers remain in the old “closed” pay structures and are unlikely to opt into the new structures due to the salary differential. NOMS is looking at all potential options to bring all staff into Fair and Sustainable terms and onto the same pay structures.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-28T16:23:25.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712494/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712494/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prisons: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she is taking to ensure that Prison Service staff undertaking the same work receive the same level of remuneration.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712496","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>Information on the NOMS workforce and staff turnover by region is published quarterly at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-offender-management-service-workforce-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-offender-management-service-workforce-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is determined to ensure that prisons are properly staffed to deliver safety and security. We will be recruiting an additional 2,500 prison officers across the prison estate and have run a localised recruitment process at 30 of our difficult to recruit sites to support the national recruitment campaign. At 31 prisons with the most difficult recruitment and retention issues, officers now receive a boost under a scheme offering higher starting pay and an additional allowance of up to £5,000 and 2000 new promotions.</p><p> </p><p>We are addressing attrition levels in a number of ways, including the appointment of 75 mentors dedicated to supporting new recruits in their first year, and the setting up of a HR Response Team to provide interventions to establishments with rising attrition.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-23T17:43:58.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712496/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712496/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prison Officers: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of trends in the level of turnover of prison staff; and what steps she is taking to support retention and recruitment of such staff.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712498","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-28","<p>The recently published White Paper on prison reform announced a major shake-up of the prison system with 2,500 extra prisons officers and new security measures to tackle drones, phones and drugs. This is a key priority for the Government as we seek to make sure our prisons are safe, decent and secure and places of reform. Safe systems of work and health and safety systems are in place across the prison estate to ensure that staff work in an environment that is as safe and secure as possible and that they are supported to deal with the challenges of working with offenders.</p><p> </p><p>The Prison Service has systems in place to deal with perpetrators quickly and robustly, with serious incidents referred to the police for prosecution. We are working with the Police and Crown Prosecution Service to ensure that prisoners who assault staff are charged wherever possible and punished appropriately. We are comprehensively reviewing how we manage violence in prisons, with a view to introducing further improvements to ensure prisons are safer places for everyone. This will provide Governors/Directors with the tools to create safer prison environments and to help reduce re-offending.</p><p> </p><p>In December 2016 the Government made a pay and pensions offer to the Prison Officers Association (POA) which included a proposed reduction in the effective pension age, which would allow officers to retire at 65. Unfortunately POA members voted to reject this deal and therefore the pension age has remain unchanged. The Prison Service regularly meet with all of the Unions representing staff in the prisons and probation services and is committed to continued constructive dialogue on all matters, including pensions and remuneration.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-28T16:16:06.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712498/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712498/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prison Officers: Retirement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the effect of raising the retirement age of prison officers to 68 years old on safety in prisons.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712499","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-27","<p>NOMS is committed to providing safe, decent and secure places of work and takes the health, safety and wellbeing of its employees extremely seriously. The Ministry of Justice is investing an extra £100m annually to boost the frontline by 2,500 officers.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS also recognises that the physical, emotional and social wellbeing of employees is paramount to attracting and retaining staff that will build a strong and capable organisation. All NOMS staff have access to an occupational health service and employee assistance programme. This includes 24 hour, 365 days a year access to signposting and counselling; trauma support services; a wide ranging health promotion website and personal wellbeing zone.</p><p> </p><p>As well as access to comprehensive occupational health services and self-referral for confidential counselling, specialist counselling such as cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) and eye movement desensitization and reprocessing (EMDR) is also available to staff who have experienced trauma. Fast track referrals to see an occupational health nurse are encouraged for staff who have experienced trauma and where staff are absent as a result of a mental and behavioural disorder an immediate referral to occupational health is recommended.</p><p> </p><p>Care teams, comprising of prison service staff, provide an immediate source of peer support and signpost staff to all of the services available.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-27T10:41:45.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712499/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712499/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prison Officers: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what support she has made available to prison offices experiencing mental health issues as a result of their employment.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712500","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-28","<p>Under the recommendations made in the 2011 Lord Hutton Report on public sector pensions, the normal pension age (retirement age) for Police Officers increased from 55 to 60, with the expectation of further reviews which may increase the age towards (or up to) the state pension age, which is currently set at between 66 and 68 depending on the individual’s date of birth.</p><p> </p><p>Those employed as police officers and members of the Police Pension Scheme fund a normal pension age of 60 through higher employee contributions than those employed as prison officers and members of the Civil Service Pension Scheme. Police officers contribute 12.44% of their pensionable pay, whereas prison officers contribute 5.45% of their pensionable pay.</p><p> </p><p>To reduce the normal pension age under the Civil Service Pension would require a change under legislation and a significant increase to contributions made by the employee into the scheme. In December 2016 however the Government made a pay and pensions offer to the Prison Officers Association (POA) which included a proposed reduction in the effective pension age, which would allow officers to retire at 65. Unfortunately POA members voted to reject this deal and therefore the pension age has remain unchanged. The Prison Service regularly meet with all of the Unions representing staff in the prisons and probation services and is committed to continued constructive dialogue on all matters, including pensions and remuneration.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-28T16:14:20.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712500/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712500/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prison Officers: Retirement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will bring forward proposals to reduce the retirement age of prison officers to bring it in line with the retirement age for police officers.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712501","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-27","<p>The Government publishes statistics on safety in custody quarterly, and updated detailed tables annually. They can be viewed here <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2016</a>. Statistics for prisoner on prisoner assaults in each of the last ten years are published in Table 4 of the ‘Safety in Custody summary table to September 2016’. The statistics will be next updated and published on 27 April 2017.<strong> </strong></p><p>Improving safety and decreasing violence is an urgent priority for this Government. We are taking immediate action to strengthen the frontline by recruiting around 2,500 more prison officers which will help us deal with emerging threats and so improve safety.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-27T10:53:56.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712501/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712501/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many incidents of prisoner-on-prisoner violence have been recorded in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712502","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>The provision of in-cell television, including the purchase of new and replacement television sets, is entirely financed from monies collected from prisoners.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-23T17:35:46.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712502/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712502/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prisons: Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 20 March 2017 to Question 67198, on prisons: electronic equipment, what proportion of the total cost of the issued 19,000 television sets is expected to be recovered.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","68612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712503","Home Office","false","2017-03-29","<p>The following link provides published data issued by the Ministry of Justice as at 31 December 2016. Data regarding foreign nationals detained in prison can be found in tab 1.6. Data on specific nationalities can be found in tab 1.7.</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/585874/prison-population-31-dec-2016.xlsx</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-29T15:32:55.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712503/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712503/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Detainees: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many EU nationals were detained in prison under immigration powers in each quarter of (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","68623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712504","Home Office","false","2017-03-28","<p>The average cost per day of immigration detention and this was last published on 23<sup>rd</sup> February 2017 at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-enforcement-data-february-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-enforcement-data-february-2017</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-28T14:54:27.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712504/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712504/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-20","Detainees: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the cost of detaining EU nationals in immigration removal centres in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","68624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712505","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>Lord Farmer was commissioned to undertake a review of family engagement, and to make proposals that will augment the Prison Safety and Reform agenda.</p><p>His report will be published in the coming months.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-23T17:53:03.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712505/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712505/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-20","Prisoners: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she plans to announce a date for the publication of the Farmer Review.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","68621"
