"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712122","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The General Pharmaceutical Council (GPhC) is the independent regulator for pharmacists, pharmacy technicians and pharmacy premises in Great Britain.</p><p>The GPhC has informed us that they are are currently analysing the responses to their recent consultation on religion, personal values and beliefs in delivering person-centred care. The GPhC will then make a decision on any changes to standards for pharmacy professionals.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-22T16:16:46.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712122/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712122/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-17","Pharmacy: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential effect of the removal of pharmacists' right to conscientious objection on the diversity of people entering that profession.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","68418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712123","Department of Health","false","2017-03-21","<p>Eligibility for NHS Continuing Healthcare is not means-tested.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Continuing Healthcare is a complete package of ongoing care arranged and funded solely by the National Health Service, where it has been assessed that the individual has a ‘primary health need’.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-21T10:32:53.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712123/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712123/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-17","Continuing Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether NHS continuing health care is means-tested at clinical commissioning group level.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","68412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712124","Department of Health","false","2017-03-22","<p>The potential association between AS03 adjuvanted pandemic A/H1N1 2009 influenza vaccine and narcolepsy is a consideration in on-going legal proceedings so it would not be appropriate to comment at this stage.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-22T10:54:19.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712124/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712124/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-17","Influenza: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the findings in respect of the potential link between the pandemic, vaccination and narcolepsy of the study, Risk of narcolepsy in children and young people receiving AS03 adjuvanted pandemic A/H1N1 2009 influenza vaccine: retrospective analysis, published in the British Medical Journal in 2013.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","68423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712125","Home Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>We are considering a number of options as to how future controls on EU migration will work, and their impact after we leave the EU. It would not be appropriate to set out further positions at this stage.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-21T15:48:35.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712125/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712125/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-17","Travel Restrictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her Department has made of the cost of additional staff resources at a departmental and agency level required by changes in travel restrictions after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","68405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712126","Home Office","false","2017-03-29","<p>Details of the support available to asylum seekers including payments toward the costs arising from the birth of a new baby can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/asylum-support/overview" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/asylum-support/overview</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on the average length of time between asylum application and maternity payment is not routinely collected and could only be provided by examination of individual case records, which would result in disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-29T15:36:58.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712126/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712126/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-17","Asylum: Maternity Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many days on average it takes between receipt of an application claiming asylum in the UK and the date of first payment of (a) maternity grant, (b) maternity allowance and (c) maternity pay.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","68415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712127","Home Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Home Office holds annual data on the number of racist hate crimes and incidents in England and Wales. We do not hold specific data relating to electoral campaigns.</p><p> </p><p>In the most recent hate crime statistical bulletin, ‘Hate Crime, England and Wales, 2015/16’, an Annex was included on the level of racially or religiously aggravated offences around the time of the EU Referendum. This analysis, based on 31 forces who supplied detailed data to the Home Office Data Hub, showed that there was an increase in the number of these offences following the announcement of the referendum result. This publication is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/hate-crime-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/hate-crime-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-03-23T14:59:38.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712127/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712127/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-17","Hate Crime: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on the number of racist (a) incidents and (b) crimes occurring during electoral campaigns in each year from 2012.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","68403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712128","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-22","<p>The findings of the Integrated Food Security Phase Classification analysis highlight the need to respond urgently to the food security crisis and prevent loss of life. In February, the Secretary of State issued a call to the international community to step up their response to the risk of famine in Somalia, South Sudan, Nigeria and Yemen. The UK has led by example, providing emergency humanitarian assistance to over 1 million people in both 2015 and 2016, and hosting a high level international event at the UN General Assembly to shine a spotlight on the forgotten crisis. In this financial year alone, we have provided lifesaving nutrition support to 889,000 women and children and food or food vouchers to 462,000 people so far. We are planning a significant contribution to Yemen in 2017/18.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-22T16:06:00.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712128/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712128/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-17","Yemen: Famine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the implications for its policies of the most recent Integrated Food Security Phase Classification Analysis report by the UN and its humanitarian partners on the humanitarian situation in Yemen; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","68360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712129","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Business Case for the UK's new support to the Palestinian Authority is in the process of publication and will appear on Development Tracker (<a href="https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/</a>) by June.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-22T16:05:04.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712129/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712129/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-17","Palestinians: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will place a copy of the Business Case and Operational Plan for the new Support to Palestinian Authority to Deliver Basic Services, Build Stability and Promote Reform in the Occupied Palestinian Territories programme in the Library.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","68425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712130","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>The risk from ligature points in prison cells is well understood. Where necessary, we provide safer cells, which are designed to minimise the availability of ligature points and thereby to make an act of suicide or self-harm as difficult as possible. This is an important part of our approach to suicide prevention. Where a prisoner is accommodated in a safer cell this forms only a part of the package of support measures that are put in place to manage the risk of self-harm or suicide.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-23T17:54:39.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712130/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712130/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-17","Prisoners: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Justice of 1 March 2017, Official Report, column 102WH, what recent assessment her Department has made of the risk of ligature points in relation to incidents of suicide or self-harm by prisoners.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","68355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712131","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Ministry of Justice has not received any such complaints, nor has it made any such assessment.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is clear that aggressive enforcement action is not acceptable. Protecting the rights of the public is our top priority, which is why we have introduced robust rules on what goods an enforcement agent can or cannot take, how and when they can enter premises and what fees they can charge.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","68373","2017-03-28T16:46:09.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712131/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712131/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-17","Equita: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many complaints she has received on (a) public contracts awarded to Equita and (b) the conduct of Equita bailiffs.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712132","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Ministry of Justice has not received any such complaints, nor has it made any such assessment.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is clear that aggressive enforcement action is not acceptable. Protecting the rights of the public is our top priority, which is why we have introduced robust rules on what goods an enforcement agent can or cannot take, how and when they can enter premises and what fees they can charge.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","68372","2017-03-28T16:46:09.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712132/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712132/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-17","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment the Government has made of mandating the use of voice recorders or body cameras for (a) bailiffs carrying out enforcement activity for public bodies and (b) other bailiffs.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712133","Scotland Office","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Scotland Office does not hold a breakdown of its costs for the Scottish Referendum in 2014.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-03-23T11:38:41.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712133/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712133/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-03-17","Sovereignty: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what the cost to the public purse was of the 2014 Scottish referendum.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","68350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712134","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-27","<p>Automatic enrolment is a policy that works. Over 7.5 million individuals have been automatically enrolled into a workplace pension by more than 465,000 employers. I am now conducting a review of the policy in order to build on that achievement.</p><p> </p><p>On 8 February 2017 I published a set of initial questions on the main themes, including coverage, engagement and future contributions and invited views and evidence to help inform our considerations. The deadline for responses was 22 March and we are now considering the responses. We are also engaging extensively with stakeholders, and an advisory group of external experts is providing insight, challenge and guidance.</p><p> </p><p>The success of automatic enrolment has been based on a partnership approach and our approach to the review will enable us to understand the views of all stakeholders, including employers and employees.</p><p> </p><p>Towards the end of 2017 we will publish a report to Parliament.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-03-27T15:37:11.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712134/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712134/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-17","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment his Department has made of the views of employers and employees on auto-enrolment workforce pensions.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","68353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712135","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-24","<p>Statistics on Personal Independence Payment Mandatory Reconsiderations can be found in published statistics in data tables 7A and 7B of:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics</a></p><p>These statistics relate to normal rules claims (i.e. excluding special rules cases for the terminally ill), and are for both new claims and Disability Living Allowance (DLA) reassessment claims.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-24T14:34:25.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712135/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712135/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-17","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many personal independence payment assessment decisions have been overturned at mandatory reconsideration stage since 1 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","68374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712136","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-23","<p>Data from 1 January 2017 have not yet been published.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the number and outcomes of Social Security and Child Support appeals is published on gov.uk. The most recent statistics, for the period October to December 2016, can be viewed at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2016" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2016</a>.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-23T13:55:39.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712136/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712136/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-17","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many personal independence payment assessment decisions have been overturned at tribunal stage since 1 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","68375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712137","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-24","<p>The system of assessing claimants’ eligibility for Personal Independent Payment (PIP) has been continually reviewed and refined in order to improve its efficiency and effectiveness. We continue to work extensively with PIP assessment providers and disability representatives to make improvements to guidance, training and audit procedures in order to ensure a quality service is maintained.</p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, as part of on-going review and improvement of PIP, we are continuing to make efforts to ensure that all decisions, whether made initially or at Mandatory Reconsideration, are the best informed decisions. For example, the department is running a series of tests which explores the different ways we can improve evidence gathering and the quality of our decision making.</p><p> </p><p>However, it is important that claimants can appeal their award decision if they are unhappy with it. Moreover, a request for an appeal does not mean that the decisions taken initially and as part of Mandatory Reconsideration were inaccurate. Claimants often provide new, relevant evidence at the tribunal stage.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-24T14:40:42.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712137/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712137/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-17","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to improve the ratio of personal independence payment cases that reach the appeal stage due to inaccurate assessments.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","68371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712138","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-22","<p>a) Average Actual Clearance Times (AACT) figures for Sure Start Maternity Grants (SSMGs) are published in Section 4.11 of the Annual Report by the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on the Social Fund 2015-16 <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/552482/social-fund-annual-report-2015-2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/552482/social-fund-annual-report-2015-2016.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>These figures show the time from receipt of application to the payment being released. In 2015-16, this was 3.54 days. It then takes 3 working days to arrive in the claimant’s bank account.</p><p> </p><p>Before a person can qualify for SSMG they have to be in receipt of a qualifying benefit. In order for the qualifying benefit to be paid, the claimant would need to have passed the Habitual Residence test for that qualifying benefit. Therefore all claimants in receipt of SSMG are habitually resident.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>b) The Average Actual Clearance Time (AACT) for Maternity Allowance (MA) for 2015/16 was 9.76 days. This shows the average time between receipt of the MA1 claim form and the decision to entitlement. The time taken to payment will depend on the circumstances of each case. The mother can apply for MA once she is 26 weeks pregnant. Payment can start any time between 11 weeks before the baby is due and the day after the baby is born, and is made when the mother leaves work.</p><p> </p><p>c) Women wishing to claim Statutory Maternity Pay (SMP) do so directly to their employer and are paid SMP as part of their pay. DWP does not deal with these cases, and holds no information on timescales for payment.</p><p> </p><p>Habitual residence is not a qualifying condition for SMP or MA, entitlement to which is based on employment, earnings and National Insurance Contributions.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-22T16:12:27.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712138/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712138/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-17","Maternity benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many days on average it takes between receipt of an application by his Department from an applicant habitually resident in the UK and the date of first payment of (a) maternity grant, (b) maternity allowance and (c) maternity pay.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","68414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712139","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-22","<p>The latest available data on personal independence payment (PIP) including clearances split by clearance type indicator and Re-assessment indicator, can be found at <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-22T15:44:49.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712139/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712139/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-17","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications for personal independence payments have been successful upon first assessment or reassessment since 2013.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","68421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712140","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-23","<p>We are carefully considering the recommendations contained in Charles Hendry’s recent report on tidal lagoons. We will inform the House following the Review.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-23T17:02:08.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712140/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712140/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712140/answer/previousversion/41822","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-17","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government will announce its decision on the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon to the House before announcing it in any other public forum.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","68362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712141","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Government is grateful to the Green Investment Bank (GIB) Board for the considered views it has provided throughout the GIB sale. All decisions taken in regard to the sale of GIB are for Ministers alone.</p><p> </p><p>As shareholder, Government works closely with the GIB Board to ensure the business operates to high standards of corporate governance at all times.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-03-23T13:55:13.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712141/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712141/answer","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712141/answer/previousversion/41823","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-17","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department was aware that the Chair of the UK Green Investment Bank was being considered for other government or commercial roles when it received advice from him on the sale of that bank; and whether his Department made an assessment of the potential effect on that advice of such consideration.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","68386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712142","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-23","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State has regular discussions with ministerial colleagues on a number of issues, including the Levy Control Framework.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-23T17:07:48.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712142/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712142/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712142/answer/previousversion/41819","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-17","Energy: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has held with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the structure of the Levy Control Framework for 2021 to 2026.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712143","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-22","<p>We have frequent conversations with key stakeholders in the automotive sector about both the challenges that leaving the EU poses and the opportunities that will become open to us, including through our partnership with the Automotive Council.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-03-22T15:46:14.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712143/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712143/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-17","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with key stakeholders in the automotive industry on the effect of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712144","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-22","<p>We anticipate that no specific UK legislation will be proposed after CETA has been ratified to bring the agreement into force in UK law.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-22T16:16:57.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712144/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712144/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-17","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment his Department has made of the primary and secondary legislative proposals likely to be required after ratification of the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement in order to bring the trade deal into effect in law.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","68356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712145","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-27","<p><em>UK-US Trade &amp; Investment Highlights </em>is a report demonstrating the depth of the current commercial relationship between the UK and the US in each of the 50 states. For each state, an estimate of the value of goods and services exported to the UK was derived by combining (a) manufacturing exports data from the US Census Bureau, (b) agricultural output data from the US Department of Agriculture, (c) services exports data from the US Bureau of Economic Analysis and (d) data on the geographical concentration of services exporters from Moody’s Analytics. Estimates of direct and indirect jobs tied to these exports were then estimated using industry-specific employment survey data from the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-03-27T16:28:59.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712145/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712145/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-17","UK Trade and Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the methodology is by which the jobs estimates referred to in the reports by his Department and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, published in March 2017, as UK Trade and Investment Highlights were collated.","false","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan","68381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712146","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-27","<p>Data on the value of trade between the UK and EU member states are available from publicly-available sources such as the Office for National Statistics, Eurostat and UN Comtrade.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-03-27T16:33:32.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712146/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/712146/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-17","UK Trade and Investment: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether analogous estimates to those used to arrive at the statistics published in the reports by his Department and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office in March 2017 as UK Trade and Investment Highlights have been made for EU member states.","false","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan","68379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711719","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-21","<p>The information requested can be found in the ‘Criminal Justice Statistics Quarterly: December 2015’ on Gov.uk</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015</a></p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-21T16:35:14.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711719/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711719/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-16","Companies: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many corporate prosecutions took place for (a) environmental crimes, (b) health and safety related offences, (c) corporate manslaughter, (d) bribery or corruption, (e) fraud, (f) tax evasion offences and (g) any other type of corporate crime in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","68306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711720","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-24","<p>The transfers of staff referred to in each of these Questions were the result of a number of machinery of government changes leading to transfers of function to my Department from HM Treasury, the Department for Work and Pensions, and the Home Office. These changes helped to rationalise and strengthen the corporate centre of the Civil Service based in my Department.</p><p> </p><p>In April 2016, Infrastructure UK (IUK) based in HM Treasury and the Major Projects Authority (MPA) based in the Cabinet Office merged to create the Infrastructure and Projects Authority within my Department. The merger brought together Government expertise in infrastructure and the financing, delivery and assurance of major projects, to support more effective management and delivery for the Government.</p><p> </p><p>In June 2016, the Civil Service Employee Policy group based in the Department for Work and Pensions transferred to my Department to become part of Civil Service Human Resources. Civil Service Employee Policy provide a professional and specialist service across government departments to develop and maintain Civil Service HR policies and practice.</p><p> </p><p>Similarly, between June and September 2016, Civil Service Learning based in the Home Office transferred to my Department and also became part of Civil Service Human Resources. Civil Service Learning provides a range of high-quality learning that aims to support and equip civil servants in the delivery of excellent public services.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the positions held by civil servants when they transferred into my Department are not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","68331 ; 68333","2017-03-24T10:42:46.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711720/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711720/answer",,,,,