"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711724","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-21","<p>The governance of LIBOR Grants complies fully with the mandated requirements of the ‘Minimum Standards for Government Grants’ which came into force on 1st December 2016. The details of any future LIBOR grants scheme open for public application will be published on the gov.uk website and advertised widely through social media and across the charity sector. All applications that meet the published criteria will be considered fully.</p><p> </p><p>No funds from Libor fines were allocated in the Spring Budget 2017 due to insufficient time being available between the Autumn Statement 2016 and the Budget, in which to conduct mandated due diligence on the significant number of applications anticipated.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","68346","2017-03-21T12:13:55.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711724/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711724/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-16","LIBOR: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure that charities are able to bid more effectively and transparently for any future allocation of funding from Libor fines.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","68345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711725","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-21","<p>The governance of LIBOR Grants complies fully with the mandated requirements of the ‘Minimum Standards for Government Grants’ which came into force on 1st December 2016. The details of any future LIBOR grants scheme open for public application will be published on the gov.uk website and advertised widely through social media and across the charity sector. All applications that meet the published criteria will be considered fully.</p><p> </p><p>No funds from Libor fines were allocated in the Spring Budget 2017 due to insufficient time being available between the Autumn Statement 2016 and the Budget, in which to conduct mandated due diligence on the significant number of applications anticipated.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","68345","2017-03-21T12:13:55.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711725/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711725/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-16","LIBOR: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons no funds from Libor fines were allocated in the Spring Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","68346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711726","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-24","<p>The Government is determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum Wage (NMW) and National Living Wage (NLW) receives them. Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW or NLW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) reviews all complaints that are referred to the department. HMRC do not collect information on employer nationality as part of minimum wage investigations.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","68279","2017-03-24T08:47:17.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711726/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711726/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-16","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many investigations have been launched into EU hauliers paying below the minimum wage to their drivers in each of the last five years for which data is available; and how many of those investigations resulted in successful prosecution.","false","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","68278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711727","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-24","<p>The Government is determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum Wage (NMW) and National Living Wage (NLW) receives them. Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW or NLW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) reviews all complaints that are referred to the department. HMRC do not collect information on employer nationality as part of minimum wage investigations.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","68278","2017-03-24T08:47:17.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711727/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711727/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-16","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the loss of tax revenue resulting from EU-based hauliers paying below the minimum wage while working in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","68279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711728","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-24","<p>HM Treasury are working with the Department for Exiting the European Union and other government departments to undertake a wide range of analysis of leaving the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>Government policy is to leave the EU and to make a success of Brexit. We are pursuing a bespoke arrangement and the best possible deal for Britain.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-03-24T14:18:51.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711728/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711728/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-16","Economic Situation: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2017 to Question 62381, whether the national and regional analysis is founded upon the assumption of reverting to World Trade Organisation rules after the UK leaves the EU; what the timescale for the analysis is; whether he plans to publish the analysis; and what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union on that analysis.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","68219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711729","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-24","<p>HM Revenue and Customs estimate that during 2015-2016, VAT compliance checks on small or medium sized businesses averaged 13.9 weeks between being opened and closed.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-24T10:15:26.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711729/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711729/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-16","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average time taken for an HM Revenue and Customs VAT investigation involving a small or medium-sized business was in the 2015-16 financial year.","false","Biography information for Chris Philp","Croydon South","Chris Philp","68224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711730","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-24","The Government has already confirmed that, in England, we will invest the £1 billion revenue we originally forecast from the Soft Drinks Industry Levy during this parliament in giving school-aged children a better and healthier future, including through doubling the primary school PE and sport premium and expanding school breakfast clubs. The Secretary of State for Education recently set out further details on this, including £415m for a new healthy pupils capital programme. The Department for Education will set out more detail in due course.<p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","68237","2017-03-24T08:36:24.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711730/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711730/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-16","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has assessed the potential merits of using money raised through the Soft Drinks Industry Levy to extend the free school meals scheme to (a) nursery schools and (b) private nurseries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","68234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711731","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-24","The Government has already confirmed that, in England, we will invest the £1 billion revenue we originally forecast from the Soft Drinks Industry Levy during this parliament in giving school-aged children a better and healthier future, including through doubling the primary school PE and sport premium and expanding school breakfast clubs. The Secretary of State for Education recently set out further details on this, including £415m for a new healthy pupils capital programme. The Department for Education will set out more detail in due course.<p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","68234","2017-03-24T08:36:24.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711731/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711731/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-16","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of using money raised from the Soft Drinks Industry Levy to support (a) nursery schools and (b) private nurseries in accessing the Children's Food Trust accreditation scheme; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","68237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711732","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-24","<p>The duties on local authorities in relation to oral health are set out in the NHS Bodies and Local Authorities (Partnership Arrangements, Care Trusts, Public Health and Local Healthwatch) Regulations 2012 ( <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2012/3094/pdfs/uksi_20123094_en.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2012/3094/pdfs/uksi_20123094_en.pdf</a> ). If a local authority fails to comply with its statutory duties, it is for the electorate to hold their local authority to account, either through the ballot box or through judicial review. The Local Government Ombudsman can investigate complaints of maladministration in local authorities, and recommend redress for individuals. It is not for central government to apply a specific penalty.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-24T14:41:21.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711732/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711732/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-16","Dental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 3 March 2017 to Question 65415, on dental health, for what reasons his Department does not know what penalty may be applied.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","68229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711733","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-21","<p>We are working with the National Housing Federation to identify the most effective location for the expanded regional pilot. More details will follow once a location has been identified.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-21T11:55:55.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711733/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711733/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-16","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress has been made on the expanded regional voluntary right to buy pilot scheme; and which (a) housing associations and (b) regions will be included in that pilot.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","68258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711734","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>The criteria for allocating the £1 billion of short-term loan finance available through the Home Building Fund is available in the fund prospectus which can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-building-fund/an-introduction-to-the-home-building-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-building-fund/an-introduction-to-the-home-building-fund</a>.</p><p>As housing is a devolved matter, the Fund is only available in England. However, £176.4 million was made available for Northern Ireland through Barnett consequentials as a result of the £3 billion Short and Long Term Home Building Fund allocations for the UK.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-23T11:05:34.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711734/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711734/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what criteria will determine allocation of the £1 billion being made available for short-term loans under the Home Building Fund.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","68263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711735","Department for Education","false","2017-03-22","<p>In 2014, the Government Equalities Office had a number of discussions with the Equality and Human Rights Commission about updating its 2009 Election Guidance in time for the 2015 election. The EHRC subsequently issued the following guidance in March 2015:</p><p><a href="https://www.equalityhumanrights.com/en/publication-download/equality-and-human-rights-law-during-election-period-guidance-local-authorities" target="_blank">https://www.equalityhumanrights.com/en/publication-download/equality-and-human-rights-law-during-election-period-guidance-local-authorities</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-22T16:40:20.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711735/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711735/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Discrimination: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many times in the last five years her Department has (a) discussed and (b) received reports from the Equality and Human Rights Commission on efforts to address discrimination during election campaigns.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","68264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711736","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Housing White Paper confirmed that the £1.2 billion Starter Homes Land Fund will be invested to support the preparations of brownfield sites for starter homes and other affordable home ownership tenures. 30 partnerships with local authorities were announced in January 2017 to identify and bring forward land opportunities. As of the end of February 2017, the Homes and Communities Agency had invested £61 million in 27 sites across the country, which have the capacity to deliver over 1,600 starter homes and other affordable home ownership units, and it is now undertaking detailed due diligence on further sites.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-23T11:04:39.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711736/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711736/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress his Department has made on rolling out the Starter Homes Land Fund.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","68287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711737","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-21","<p>We will publish data about public libraries in England shortly.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-03-21T16:09:19.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711737/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711737/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-16","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the post on the Libraries Taskforce blog of 8 August 2016, entitled Book dataset first steps, for what reason the library provisions dataset has not yet been published.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","68299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711738","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-22","<p>The Government has published a consultation on the £300 million discretionary relief scheme announced at the Spring Budget 2017. The consultation sets out a proposed allocation methodology and indicative allocations for individual billing authorities, and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/discretionary-business-rates-relief-scheme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/discretionary-business-rates-relief-scheme</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-22T10:16:51.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711738/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711738/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711738/answer/previousversion/41619","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-16","Non-domestic Rates: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much discretionary relief for business rates hard cases will be available to businesses in the London Borough of Newham.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","68301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711739","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-22","<p>The effect of the revaluation on properties in East Ham constituency will depend on the specific circumstances and location of the relevant properties, including their changing entitlement to business rate reliefs.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-22T10:16:08.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711739/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711739/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711739/answer/previousversion/41621","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-16","Non-domestic Rates: East Ham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the number of businesses that will pay (a) higher and (b) lower rates in East Ham constituency following the business rates revaluation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","68302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711740","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-22","<p>This data is not held centrally.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-22T10:16:24.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711740/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711740/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711740/answer/previousversion/41622","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-16","Non-domestic Rates: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much was paid in rates by businesses in the London Borough of Newham in the most recent year for which data is available; and what he expects the total amount paid to be following revaluation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","68303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711741","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-21","<p>The 32 social impact bonds (SIB) have been developed by a range of local and central government commissioners so DCMS does not hold this information. We are working closely with partners to develop our understanding of the costs of setting up and running a SIB.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-03-21T13:41:51.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711741/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711741/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-16","Social Impact Bonds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of the (a) staffing, (b) advertising and marketing and (c) other administrative costs of developing each of the 32 currently operational social impact bonds.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","68305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711742","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-24","<p>My officials are in contact with Sport England regarding the Two Trees High School Site in Denton. Sport England have been in regular discussions with Tameside MBC, Andrew Gwynne MP and other key local stakeholders about the future of the site.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England will continue to provide advice on this and I hope this will help to achieve an outcome that provides the local community with sustainable sports facilities that help more people to get active.</p><p> </p><p>My department will continue to monitor the situation with interest and to engage as appropriate.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-03-24T13:14:04.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711742/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711742/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-16","Two Trees School Denton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will hold discussions with Sport England on the disposal request for the Two Trees High School site in Denton; and if she will meet the hon. Member for Denton and Reddish to discuss that request.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","68284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711743","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Government is working with the voluntary sector to assess the impact of leaving the EU, including how the sector’s workforce may be affected. Securing an agreement that will guarantee the status of EU nationals here and UK nationals in the EU is one of government’s top priorities.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-03-21T13:40:25.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711743/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711743/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-16","Voluntary Organisations: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent estimate she has made of the number of non-UK EU nationals working in the UKs voluntary sector.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","68343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711744","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-23","<p>We have no such assessment . From April, large employers will be required to publish any differences in average earnings and bonuses paid to women and men. The Government’s Equalities Office (GEO) are responsible for policies regarding gender equality.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","68325","2017-03-23T16:07:57.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711744/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711744/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-16","Culture: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the gender pay gap in the cultural industries.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","68323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711745","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-24","<p>Over 16,000 premises within the constituency have received access to superfast broadband because of government intervention. A further 24,600 are able to connect as a result of commercially funded rollout.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-24T15:12:25.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711745/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711745/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-16","Broadband: Wealden","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many premises in Wealden constituency have access to superfast broadband through the Broadband Delivery UK scheme.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","68324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711746","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-23","<p>We have no such assessment . From April, large employers will be required to publish any differences in average earnings and bonuses paid to women and men. The Government’s Equalities Office (GEO) are responsible for policies regarding gender equality.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","68323","2017-03-23T16:07:57.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711746/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711746/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-16","Culture: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to address the gender pay gap in cultural industries.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","68325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711747","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-24","<p>Third party analysis by Think Broadband puts current superfast coverage in the constituency at 89.3%. Coverage is likely to increase further both as a result of the current Go eSussex project (http://www.goesussex.co.uk/) and a potential future project, for which an Invitation to Tender is expected to be issued shortly.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-24T15:12:53.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711747/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711747/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-16","Broadband: Wealden","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of when superfast broadband coverage in Wealden constituency will reach (a) 90 and (b) 95 per cent.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","68326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711748","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-21","<p>On the 27 February, the Department published progress one year on from the report of the Government Expert Working Group on Football Supporter Ownership and Engagement. This progress report is a summary of the achievements made so far by the football authorities, supporter representative groups and government to implement the Working Group's recommendations. The report is available at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/football-expert-working-group-progress-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/football-expert-working-group-progress-report</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In particular, changes are already in place to help Supporters Trusts bid to buy insolvent clubs, as well as requiring all 92 professional clubs to meet with their supporters at least twice a year to discuss the matters of most importance. These meetings lead the way in ensuring fans are better informed, and consulted on club activities.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-03-21T13:54:31.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711748/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711748/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-16","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to promote opportunities for supporters to have increased involvement in the running of football clubs.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711749","Department for Education","false","2017-03-31","<p>The Department has paid the following sums to the Baker Dearing Trust (BDT):</p><p> </p><p>(a) 2014/15 - £213,191</p><p>(b) 2015/16 - £157,364</p><p>(c) 2016/17 –£138,341 (from 1 April 2016 – 31 January 2017)</p><p> </p><p>BDT provide advice, guidance and pre-approval support to proposer groups developing applications to establish UTCs. The Department funds this work through a competitively tendered grant award.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-31T08:44:54.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711749/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711749/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","University Technical Colleges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department paid any sums in to the Baker-Dearing Trust in (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Michael Gove","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","68217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711750","Department for Education","false","2017-03-24","<p>Future availability of apprenticeships is dependent on employers recruiting apprentices and offering opportunities. Published data on projected apprenticeship starts is not available.</p><p> </p><p>We want to encourage more employers to offer apprenticeships and our reforms give employers the opportunity to do so - employers are designing new apprenticeships that meet their business and skills needs.</p><p> </p><p>We are putting control of the funding for apprenticeships firmly in the hands of employers, so they can invest in quality training. Publication of the Register of Apprenticeship Training Providers on 14 March 2017 means that employers have a real choice in the training they select, so that they get the skills they need to grow their business.</p><p> </p><p>The Apprenticeships Levy comes into effect from April 2017, as part of a wider suite of reforms to improve the quality and sustainability of the apprenticeship system.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-24T13:36:30.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711750/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711750/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of apprenticeship starts in 2017-18 are expected to be offered by businesses (a) paying and (b) not paying the Apprenticeship Levy.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","68218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711751","Department for Education","false","2017-03-23","<p>The current invitation to tender for the delivery of apprenticeships to employers who don’t pay the levy has a maximum initial contract award of £5 million for each successful training provider applicant. This initial limit was put in place to ensure adequate coverage of geographic and sector areas as well as adequate capacity and capability to deliver at that level.</p><p>In total, 97% of providers who currently hold funding agreements with the Skills Funding Agency currently have contracts of lower than £5 million.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-23T12:52:14.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711751/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711751/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Apprentices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of introducing a cap on the level of financial support available for each apprenticeship contract; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","68220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711752","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>We are committed to making this a country where everyone has a fair chance to go as far as his or her talent and hard work will allow. The pupil premium provides schools with significant additional funding - £2.5bn this year alone – to raise the achievement of their disadvantaged pupils and so close the attainment gap. Our guarantee to maintain current per-pupil funding levels for the rest of this Parliament will ensure schools continue to have the support they need to improve disadvantaged pupils’ outcomes.</p><p>This year, disadvantaged pupils in South Cambridgeshire will benefit from £2.6 million in pupil premium funding.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-04-27T11:36:59.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711752/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711752/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Schools: South Cambridgeshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to close the deprivation attainment gap in South Cambridgeshire constituency.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","68233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711753","Department for Education","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Government is committed to creating a country that works for everyone, regardless of their background. We want all children to reach their full potential and to succeed in adult life.</p><p> </p><p>Disadvantage has a significant impact on pupils’ attainment. This impact is seen throughout the school system and compounded in areas of disadvantage. In recognition of that, our formula recognises educational disadvantage in its widest sense, using different indicators within the deprivation factor into target funding widely. We want, in particular, to include those pupils who are not necessarily eligible for free school meals, but whose families are still struggling to get by.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-23T17:49:00.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711753/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711753/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of recent changes to the National Funding Formula on the deprivation attainment gap in schools.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","68232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711754","Department for Education","false","2017-03-21","<p>Statistics covering support paid by Student Finance England (SFE) to English and EU domiciled students are published annually by the Student Loans Company (SLC) in the Statistical First Release (SFR) <em>‘Student Support for Higher Education in England’.</em></p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx</a></p><p>Table 3A of the SFR shows how much means-tested support was paid to full-time English domiciled students as non-repayable maintenance grants up to the academic year 2015/16. In the academic year 2015/16, a full maintenance grant was available to students with a household residual income up to £25,000, and a partial grant to those with a household residual income up to £42,620. For comparison, table 2 of the SFR provides an overview of all support awarded to applicants up to the academic year 2015/16.</p><p>Larger maintenance loans have been available in place of maintenance grants to help with living costs for full-time students entering higher education since August 2016. Table 6.3 of the SFR shows early indicative data (two months into the academic year) on maintenance grants awarded in the academic year 2016/17. More complete information for the academic year 2016/17 will be published in November 2017.</p><p>Other non-repayable targeted support is available to eligible students with disabilities, or with adult or child dependants, however information on the payment of these to students from low income families is not available.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-03-21T17:34:01.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711754/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711754/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much (a) in total and (b) as a proportion of total annual expenditure paid to students by Student Finance England was spent on non-repayable support paid to students from low income families in England in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","68304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711755","Department for Education","false","2017-03-27","<p>The Department has not issued any guidance on the provision of sanitary products in schools.</p><p>Schools have discretion over how they use their funding and if they wish to make these products available to disadvantaged pupils they are free to do so.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-03-27T13:54:18.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711755/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711755/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Pupils: Period Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance her Department has issued to schools on the provision of sanitary products for children from a low income background.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","68295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711756","Department for Education","false","2017-03-21","<p>The levy is being introduced to fund a step change in apprenticeship numbers and quality. Levying all employers with annual pay bills over £3 million is the simplest, fairest and most objective way of implementing the levy which is charged at 0.5% of an employer’s annual pay bill. We have been clear that there can be no exemptions to this.</p><p> </p><p>We expect local authorities to work closely with the schools in their areas to ensure schools contributing to the levy can access the funding for apprenticeship training and assessment in order to get the valuable skills they need.</p><p> </p><p>There are already apprenticeships that schools can access, including for Teaching Assistants, business administration and early years. Employer-led groups are also currently developing high-quality apprenticeship standards specifically for schools, including a teaching apprenticeship and school business manager apprenticeships.</p><p> </p><p>We recently published guidance for schools on apprenticeships, and how the apprenticeship levy and public sector apprenticeship target apply to schools in England on gov.uk available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/598603/Schools__guide_to_apprenticeship_reforms.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/598603/Schools__guide_to_apprenticeship_reforms.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-21T16:33:30.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711756/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711756/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to review the requirement on schools to pay the apprenticeship levy.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","68297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711757","Department for Education","false","2017-03-24","<p>Statistics on student support awards and payments are published annually by the Student Loans Company (SLC) in the Statistical First Release (SFR) ‘Student Support for Higher Education in England’. The latest figures available refer to the 2016/17 Academic Year for student support awards and 2015/16 for actual payments, and are available at the link below.</p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx</a></p><p>Statistics in the SFR are at the national level.</p><p><strong>Students who were paid full-time tuition fee loans from the Batley and Spen Parliamentary Constituency</strong><sup>1</sup><strong>, West Yorkshire and England</strong></p><p><strong>Academic years: 2009/10 to 2015/16</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Academic Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Batley and Spen</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>West Yorkshire</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>England</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>2,950</p></td><td><p>24,520</p></td><td><p>790,255</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>3,160</p></td><td><p>25,730</p></td><td><p>832,610</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>3,410</p></td><td><p>26,885</p></td><td><p>887,270</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>3,650</p></td><td><p>27,770</p></td><td><p>925,465</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>3,955</p></td><td><p>28,980</p></td><td><p>965,540</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>4,225</p></td><td><p>30,245</p></td><td><p>973,395</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16 <sup>[3]</sup></p></td><td><p>4,525</p></td><td><p>32,030</p></td><td><p>1,006,715</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Student Loans Company (SLC)</p><ol><li>Based on the student’s address at the time of the application.</li><li>Figures are rounded to the nearest 5.</li><li>Data for 2015/16 is effective 31/08/2016, this is still provisional as payments still happen following the end of the academic year.</li><li>Batley &amp; Spen Constituency and West Yorkshire have been derived from the home address (postcode region) of the student as stated on application for student finance.</li></ol><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","68293","2017-03-24T14:58:22.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711757/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711757/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Students: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many full-time tuition fee loans were paid to students from (a) Batley and Spen constituency and (b) West Yorkshire in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","68298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711758","Department for Education","false","2017-03-27","<p>The government knows how important swift access to defibrillators can be in cases of cardiac arrest, which is why we are encouraging schools to purchase a defibrillator as part of their first-aid equipment. To help enable schools to do so, the Department for Education have negotiated a deal with NHS Supply Chain to offer defibrillators to schools at a reduced cost, and have published advice on installing and maintaining defibrillators on school premises.</p><p> </p><p>Since the scheme was launched in 2014, 1982 defibrillators have been purchased through this route. We continue to work with the sector to raise awareness of the scheme and to refine our guidance to schools on installing and maintaining these devices.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-03-27T14:07:45.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711758/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711758/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Educational Institutions: Defibrillators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans her Department has to ensure the provision of defibrillators in educational establishments.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","68267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711759","Department for Education","false","2017-03-29","<p>The Education Funding Agency (EFA) received a section 77 application from Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council on 15 March 2017. The application is currently being reviewed by officials at the EFA. The Secretary of State will also consider the recommendation from the School Playing Fields Advisory Panel before making her final decision. She has therefore asked the official dealing with the application to contact the hon. Member for Denton and Reddish to discuss this matter when they have completed their initial review.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-29T14:11:03.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711759/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711759/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Two Trees School Denton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2016 to Question 42557, on the Two Trees School, Denton, whether a section 77 application from Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council has yet been received; and if she or officials of her Department will meet the hon. Member for Denton and Reddish to discuss that matter.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","68291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711760","Department for Education","false","2017-03-23","<p>The following table provides the number of full time equivalent classroom teachers in service in state funded schools in Batley and Spen constituency, West Yorkshire and England in each year from November 2010 to November 2015.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Batley and Spen</strong></p></td><td><p>770</p></td><td><p>770</p></td><td><p>820</p></td><td><p>840</p></td><td><p>840</p></td><td><p>850</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>West Yorkshire</strong></p></td><td><p>16,820</p></td><td><p>16,290</p></td><td><p>16,800</p></td><td><p>16,470</p></td><td><p>17,030</p></td><td><p>17,340</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>England</strong></p></td><td><p>375,260</p></td><td><p>371,670</p></td><td><p>379,340</p></td><td><p>385,460</p></td><td><p>388,650</p></td><td><p>387,690</p></td></tr></tbody></table><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Source: School Workforce Census</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>Figures are rounded to the nearest 10 FTE classroom teachers.</p><p>In 2011, two schools in the Batley and Spen did not provide data on teachers, so figures are not comparable with other years. <strong><br> </strong></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-23T17:48:19.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711760/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711760/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-16","Classroom Assistants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many full-time equivalent classroom teachers were employed in schools in (a) Batley and Spen constituency, (b) West Yorkshire and (c) England in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","68292"
