"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711358","Department for Education","false","2017-03-23","<p>We are in the process of developing pilots to be delivered during 2017/18 and 2018/19. The funding will be targeted on interventions that test and deliver the most effective approaches to breaking down barriers to lifelong learning.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-23T12:41:53.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711358/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711358/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-15","Lifelong Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 4.11 of the Spring Budget 2017, when the funding for lifelong learning pilots will be rolled out; and how that funding will be allocated.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","68165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711359","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-20","<p>Tax relief was claimed for 45 video games with a financial year of completion of 2014-15 and for 65 video games with a financial year of completion of 2015-16. The limited number of returns means it is not possible to present regional statistics while maintaining the standards of HM Revenue and Customs’ statistical disclosure controls.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-20T11:57:41.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711359/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711359/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-15","Video Games: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many companies have claimed video games tax relief in each financial year since 2014; and in which regions of the UK those companies are located.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","68115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711360","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-20","<p>HM Revenue and Customs estimate that around 790,000 customers failed to submit their online Self Assessment tax return by the 31 January 2017 deadline. This is roughly 7% of the returns that were due by 31 January 2017.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-20T11:44:59.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711360/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711360/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-15","Taxation: Self-assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of people who missed the 31 January 2017 deadline for submitting tax returns.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","68122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711361","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-24","<p>The figures asked for are not readily available and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Annual statistics on the total number of transactions and total Stamp Duty Land Tax receipts by Parliamentary Constituency (including Wimbledon) are published by HM Revenue and Customs in the annual ‘UK Stamp Tax Statistics’. These publications cover the financial years from 2012-13 to 2015‑16. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-stamp-tax-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-stamp-tax-statistics</a></p><p>Table 3.6 of the latest release, for 2015-16, also contains statistics broken down by the price band of the property and the region (eg London).</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/556350/AnnualStampTaxes-Release-Sep16.xlsx</p><p>Statistics relating to 2016-17 are due to be published in September</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-24T08:42:00.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711361/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711361/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-15","Housing: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many residential property transactions valued at (a) £125,000.01 to £250,000, (b) £250,000.01 to £925,000.01, (c) £925,000 to £1.5 million and (d) over £1.5 million there have been in Wimbledon constituency since 2012; and what the total stamp duty land tax revenue generated by those transactions was in (i) 2012, (ii) 2013, (iii) 2014, (iv) 2015 and (v) 2016 in each of those price bands.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","68065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711362","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-24","<p>My Department is currently consulting on the £300 million discretionary relief scheme. The scheme will enable local authorities to help those individual businesses that are facing increased rates bills. Local authorities will be responsible for the design of local schemes which will include setting the eligibility criteria that will apply. The consultation is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/discretionary-business-rates-relief-scheme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/discretionary-business-rates-relief-scheme</a></p><p>Additionally, the £110 million Supporting Small Business Relief Scheme will also be available to assist those ratepayers losing small business rates relief or rural rate relief as a result of revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-24T14:42:04.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711362/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711362/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether shared workspaces for the self-employed and small businesses will be eligible for the proposed business rate relief discretionary support.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","68017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711363","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-23","<p>Freedom of Information (FOI) statistics are Official Statistics and are governed by the standards set out by the UK Statistics Authority (UKSA) in their Code of Practice. To publish information outside of the release timetable would be a breach of Protocol 2 of the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The latest FOI statistics were published in December 2016 and are available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/freedom-of-information-statistics-july-to-september-2016--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/freedom-of-information-statistics-july-to-september-2016--2</a></p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-23T15:47:10.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711363/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711363/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-15","Treasury: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average response rate was of his Department to individual Freedom of Information requests in each month since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","68052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711364","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Government has published the total liability for all projects procured through the former Private Finance Initiative and current Private Finance 2 initiative on an annual basis. The latest data is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2016-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2016-summary-data</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-03-20T11:59:28.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711364/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711364/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-15","Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has made an estimate of the amount of additional liability to the taxpayer above the initial cost of completed private finance initiative projects.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","68054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711365","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-20","<p>The new Customs Declarations Service is designed to accommodate increased volumes in customs declarations, including any arising as a consequence of the UK’s departure from the European Union. HM Revenue and Customs continues to monitor the position.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-20T11:40:49.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711365/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711365/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-15","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential cost of updating the incoming Customs Declaration Service in order to cope with customs declarations once the UK leaves the EU customs union.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","68214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711366","Department for Education","false","2017-03-29","<p>The Department for Education will invest over £24 billion on school buildings between 2016-17 and 2020-21 financial years, which includes funding for new school places, including the free schools programme, and funding to maintain and improve the condition of the school estate, including the Priority School Building Programme. The Department confirms annual funding allocations for specific programmes in the spring for the financial year ahead, based on the latest forecasts of programme delivery.</p><p>The Department’s Supplementary Estimate Memorandum for 2016-17 financial year sets the budget for the Priority School Building Programme as £1,030 million and that for Free Schools, University Technical Colleges and Studio Schools as £1,116 million. Spending plans for 2017-18 will be published alongside the forthcoming 2017-18 Main Estimate. The Memorandum is available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/Education/Department-for-Education-Supplementary-Estimate-2016-17-Memorandum.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/Education/Department-for-Education-Supplementary-Estimate-2016-17-Memorandum.pdf</a></p><p>Detailed spending plans for future financial years will be set out in future Main and Supplementary Estimates. This will include the Department’s plans for the £216 million funding for school maintenance referred to in table 2.1 of the Spring Budget 2017.[1]</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] The £230 million referred to in item 3 of the table includes Barnett consequentials.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","68187 ; 68216","2017-03-29T14:11:48.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711366/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711366/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-15","Schools: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to item 3 in table 2.1 of the Spring Budget 2017, how the school capital funding will be allocated.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","68192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711367","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Office for National Statistics produce statistics for the public good, according to the professional standards set out in the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. The Code applies to all UK bodies that produce official statistics, including my Department.</p><p>My Department works closely with officials from the Office for National Statistics on issues relating to housing data. We are currently helping the UK Statistics Authority to carry out their Systemic Review of Housing Statistics (embracing all data providers).</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-23T11:07:55.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711367/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711367/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Housing: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to improve the clarity and accessibility of housing data published by the Office for National Statistics.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","68200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711368","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-20","<p>The Department is carefully considering the recommendations made by Mr Ollerenshaw. The Government’s response to the review’s findings will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-20T15:33:10.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711368/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711368/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Local Council Tax Support Schemes Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when his Department plans to publish its response to the Ollerenshaw Review of Local Council Tax Support Schemes, published on 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","68201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711369","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>The campaign has had a real impact in helping drive footfall and bringing local communities together, delivering a key strand of the Government’s town centre policy to create vibrant and sustainable high streets and markets. It recognises that markets make a vital contribution to local communities and economies.</p><p>The Government part-funded the National Association of British Market Authorities to run the campaign between 2012 and 2016, ensuring that there was a focus on encouraging young people of all ages to participate, including places holding specific youth markets. This year’s campaign, which will take place between 17 and 31 May, will again focus on how to attract young people to markets – not only as traders but also as shoppers.</p><p>The National Market Traders’ Federation works closely with the National Association of British Market Authorities on “Love Your Local Market”. Government welcomes the National Market Traders’ Federation own, successful National Youth Market initiative, which is run in partnership with Manchester Markets. This is aimed at 16-30 year olds who have a great business idea to test out.</p><p>This Government will continue to help promote the campaigns through visits and publicity.</p><p> </p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","68109 ; 68110","2017-03-23T14:28:52.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711369/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711369/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Markets: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what support his Department provides to locally led initiatives that promote market trading as an employment or business path for young people.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","68053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711370","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-22","<p>At the Budget on 8 March the Chancellor announced a new relief scheme for pubs with a rateable value below £100,000. Under the scheme, eligible pubs will receive a £1000 discount on rate bills. My Department will shortly consult on guidance which will include proposals on the eligibility criteria and other aspects of the scheme.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","68062","2017-03-22T16:50:20.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711370/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711370/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Non-domestic Rates: Wimbledon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many businesses in Wimbledon constituency will be eligible for the £1,000 business rate discount for public houses announced in paragraph 4.5 of the Spring Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","68063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711371","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-20","<p>There have been no recent discussions with the devolved administrations on whether the Redundancy Payments (Continuity of Employment in Local Government etc.) (Modification) Order 1999 requires to be updated.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-20T12:43:44.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711371/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711371/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Local Government: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent discussions he has had with the devolved administrations on whether the Redundancy Payments (Continuity of Employment in Local Government etc.) (Modification) Order 1999 requires to be updated.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","68014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711372","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-20","<p>We have set out a clear manifesto commitment to tackle aggressive parking enforcement and excessive private parking charges. This Government is taking steps to tackle rogue and unfair practices by private parking operators. We have put in place a range of measures to reform the behaviour of private parking companies, including the banning of wheel clamping and towing.</p><p>The discussion paper entitled ‘Parking reform: tackling unfair practices’, sought thoughts and comments on the private parking sector. My Department published a summary of the responses on 11 May 2016. I am actively considering responses to the discussion paper, and options for reform.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-20T12:42:11.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711372/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711372/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Parking: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that private parking ticket costs are not excessive.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","68027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711373","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-24","<p>FOI statistics are Official Statistics and as such are governed by the standards set out by the UK Statistics Authority (UKSA) in their Code of Practice. To publish information outside of the release timetable would be a breach of Protocol 2 of the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.</p><p>The latest Freedom of Information statistics were published in December 2016 and are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/freedom-of-information-statistics-july-to-september-2016--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/freedom-of-information-statistics-july-to-september-2016--2</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-24T12:07:09.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711373/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711373/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Department for Communities and Local Government: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the average response rate was of his Department to individual Freedom of Information requests in each month since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","68038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711374","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-22","<p>At the Budget on 8 March the Chancellor announced a new relief scheme for pubs with a rateable value below £100,000. Under the scheme, eligible pubs will receive a £1000 discount on rate bills. My Department will shortly consult on guidance which will include proposals on the eligibility criteria and other aspects of the scheme.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","68063","2017-03-22T16:50:20.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711374/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711374/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Licensed Premises: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether (a) restaurants and (b) wine bars will be eligible for the £1,000 business rate discount for public houses announced in paragraph 4.5 of the Spring Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","68062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711375","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Deregulation Act 2015 introduced protection for tenants against retaliatory eviction. Where a tenant makes a genuine complaint about the condition of their property that has not been addressed by their landlord, their complaint has been verified by a local authority inspection, and the local authority has served either an improvement notice or a notice of emergency remedial action, the landlord cannot evict that tenant for 6 months using the ‘no-fault’ eviction procedure under section 21 of the Housing Act 1988. The landlord is also required to ensure that the repairs are completed.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-23T11:08:41.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711375/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711375/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to protect tenants in the private rental sector from potential retaliatory evictions.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","68106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711376","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>The Government has published ‘How to Rent: the checklist for renting in England’ to help tenants to understand their rights and responsibilities when renting a property in the private rented sector. This can be accessed online at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/how-to-rent" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/how-to-rent</a>. The guide provides detailed information on each stage of the renting process, including how to get help if things go wrong.</p><p>The Assured Shorthold Tenancy Notices and Prescribed Requirements (England) Regulations 2015 made it a requirement for landlords to supply a copy of the ‘How to Rent Guide’ to tenants in relation to an assured shorthold tenancy of a dwelling-house in England granted on or after 1st October 2015. The Department recommends that this document is given at the start of a new tenancy. If this document is not supplied, landlords are not able to evict tenants using a Section 21 notice.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-23T11:06:52.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711376/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/711376/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-15","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to improve awareness for tenants in the private rental sector of their rights and responsibilities as tenants.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","68107"
